"Fekete I., Halász J., Kramoperger Z., Krausz E.","Study of litter decomposition intensity in litter manipulative trials in Síkfokút cambisols",2008,"Cereal Research Communications","36","SUPPL. 5",,"1779","1782",,,10.1556/CRC.36.2008.Suppl.3,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80053070700&partnerID=40&md5=bca54fb4f3b8e2ecf5213676dce89ef3","Department of Environmental Sciences, College of Nyíregyháza, Sóstói u. 31/b, H-4400 Nyíregyháza, Hungary; Institute of Biology, College of Nyíregyháza, Hungary; Ecological Institute, University of Debrecen, Hungary","Fekete, I., Department of Environmental Sciences, College of Nyíregyháza, Sóstói u. 31/b, H-4400 Nyíregyháza, Hungary; Halász, J., Institute of Biology, College of Nyíregyháza, Hungary; Kramoperger, Z., Ecological Institute, University of Debrecen, Hungary; Krausz, E., Department of Environmental Sciences, College of Nyíregyháza, Sóstói u. 31/b, H-4400 Nyíregyháza, Hungary","Soil organic matter supply is mainly derived from plant litter. Waring & Schlesinger (1985) found that plant litter decomposition provides 69-87% of nutrients required for forest development. The global climate change caused local changes in Hungary (Várallyay, 2007), which can influence the litter production of the natural vegetation. In the frame of Síkfokút DIRT (Detritus Input and Removal Treatments) project the effect of litter amount was studied on the activity of soil microbes (Fekete et al., 2007), and speed of organic matter decomposition applying different kind of wood, leaf, root and different amount of plant litter. In this paper we discuss the degree of decomposition of leaf litter and cellulose cotton wool placed in the soil in the respect of different litter treatment plots.","DIRT; Leaf litter and cellulose decomposition activity; Litter bags; Síkfokút site","Gossypium hirsutum",,,,,,"Atlas, R.M., (1988) Microbiology: Fundamentals and Applications, , 2 nd ed. Collier Macmillan publishers, London; Batjes, N.H., Mitigation of atmospheric CO 2 concentrations by increased carbon sequestration in the soil (1998) Biol. Fertil Soils, 27, pp. 230-235; Berg, B., Litter decomposition and organic matter turnover in northern forest soils (2000) For. Ecol. Manage, 133, pp. 13-22; Berg, B., Ekbohm, G., Litter mass-loss rates and decomposition patterns in some needle and leaf litter types. Long term decomposition in a scots pine forest Vll (1991) Can. J. Bot., 69, pp. 1449-1456; Berg, B., Hannus, K., Popoff, T., Theander, O., Changes in organic chamical components of needle litter during decomposition. Long-term decomposition in a scots pine forest I (1982) Can. J. Bot., 60, pp. 1310-1319; Cook, R.C., Rayner, A.D.M., (1984) Ecology of Saprotrophic Fungi, , Longman, London; Clymo, R.S., Peat (1983) Ecosystem of the Word 4A, pp. 159-224. , Mires: Swamp, Bog, Fen and Moor. Ed. Goodall D. W, Elsevier, Amsterdam; Fekete, I., Varga, Cs., Kotroczó, Zs., Krakomperger, Zs., Tóth, J.A., The effect of temperature and moisture on enzyme activity in Síkfokút Site (2007) Cereal Research Communications, 35 (2), pp. 381-384; Fontaine, S., Mariotti, A., Abbadie, L., The priming effect of organic matter: A question of microbial competition? (2003) Soil Biol. Biochem, 35, pp. 837-843; Gosz, J.R., Likens, G.E., Bormann, F.H., Nutrient release from decomposing leaf and branch litter int he Hubbard Brook Forest, New Hampshire (1973) Ecol. Monogr, 43, pp. 173-191; Hamer, U., Marschner, B., Priming effects of sugars, amino acids, organic acids and catechol on the mineralization of lignin and peat (2002) J. Plant Nutr. Soil Sci, 165, pp. 261-268; Hobbie, S.E., Temperature and plant species control over litter decomposition in Alaskan tundra (1996) Ecological Monographs, 66, pp. 503-522; Kirk, T.K., Connors, W.J., Zeikus, G., Requirment for a growth substrate during lignin decomposition by two wood-rotting fungi (1976) Appl. Environ. Microbiol, 32, pp. 192-194; Melillo, J.M., Aber, J.D., Linkins, A.E., Ricca, A., Fry, B., Nadelhoffer, K.J., Carbon and nitrogen dynamics along the decay continuum: Plant litter to soil organic matter (1989) Plant Soil, 115, pp. 180-198; Swift, M.J., Heal, O.W., Anderson, J.M., Decomposition in terrestrial ecosystems (1979) Studies in Ecology, p. 5. , Blackwell Scientific Publications, Oxford; Szabó, I.M., Az általános talajtan biológiai alapjai (1986) Mezogazdasági Kiadó, pp. 215-219. , Budapest; Szegi, J., Talajmikrobiológiai vizsgálati módszerek (1979) Mezogazdasági Kiadó, pp. 245-247. , Budapest; Takeda, H., Interactions between plant and decomposer populations in forest ecosystems, a mechanism of biodiversity maintenance, Jpn (1994) J. Ecol, 44, pp. 211-222; Troeh, F.R., Thompson, W.J., (2005) Soil and Soil Fertility, p. 108. , 6th Edition Blackwell Publishing; Várallyay, G., A globális klímaváltozás: Hazai hatások és válaszok (A VAHAVA Jelentés) (2007) Agrokémia és Talajtan, 56 (1), pp. 199-202. , Láng I., Csete L. és Jolánkai M. szerk; Warning, R.H., Schlesinger, W.H., (1985) Forest Ecosystems: Concepts and Management, , Academic Press, New York, USA","Fekete, I.; Department of Environmental Sciences, College of Nyíregyháza, Sóstói u. 31/b, H-4400 Nyíregyháza, Hungary; email: feketeist@freemail.hu",,,,,,,,01333720,,CRCMC,,"English","Cereal Res. Commun.",Conference Paper,Scopus,2-s2.0-80053070700
